  "notes_normalized": "Cannabis is legal in Alaska under state law for recreational adult use. Medical cannabis is not broadly legal in Alaska. Cannabis remains federally illegal in United States.",
  "notes_raw": "style=\"background:#196E92;\" | {{Hs|1}} It was first legalized by the court ruling Ravin v. State in 1975, but later recriminalized by Measure 2 in 1990. The Alaska Supreme Court thereby became the first and only U.S. state or federal court to announce a constitutional right to privacy that protects some level of marijuana use and possession. The measure imposed a penalty of up to 90 days in jail and a fine of up to $1000 for simple possession. The measure allowed patients with a doctor's recommendation to possess up to of cannabis or grow six plants. Possession of was made a misdemeanor punishable by up to a year in jail. Possession of over was made a felony.",
